Text.Value: I see.
Rest well. We'll need our strength.
This isn't all bad. The tadpoles seem to have given us powers.
Maybe. But we might get lucky. We're overdue some good fortune.
You don't trust Wyll?
It's late. We can talk about this in the morning.
You don't trust Lae'zel?
If we're to survive, we need to trust each other.
You and that githyanki.
You and Gale.
Outside threats, perhaps.

EditorData.AnimationTags: pointing at her head when refereing to the threats inside them

Text.Value: We did just talk about it. Let's rest.
She's a stranger to these parts, same as you. But you strike me as reasonable, while she has her own agenda. I'd be surprised if our interests remained aligned.
She's not of this world. I'd be surprised if our interests remained aligned.
We were just discussing the next steps.
You don't trust our companions?
Each hour that passes, the thing inside us grows. We need to find a healer. Let's wake up at first light.
I have my reasons - they're nothing for you to be concerned about.

EditorData.logicalname: PLAYER DOESN'T KNOW SH IS SHAR WORSHIPPER

Text.Value: No, you've lost me. No idea what you're talking about.
Agreed. Our top priority, as far as I'm concerned.
...But speaking of focus, let's be clear: come daybreak, finding a healer is our first priority, yes?
Fine. But not for too long.
You like to stir things up, don't you? Stop looking for trouble and stay focused.
If anyone has me concerned, it's you. You haven't exactly been open about yourself.
Don't fret. We need some rest.
He's a wizard. All they care about is power.
I wasn't confiding in anyone. I was just talking.
I'd be careful with Wyll.
These powers must have a price. They come from invasive parasites that will turn us into mind flayers.
Good. We might even get lucky and find one right away. As I see it, we're overdue some good fortune. Rest well.
I think I've been more than candid - you know about my faith, for one thing.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referring to her Shar worship, which  the player is aware of here.
EditorData.logicalname: PLAYER KNOWS SH IS SHAR WORSHIPPER

Text.Value: You and the pale fellow.
Agreed. The sooner we find someone to help us, the better.
There are lit fuses in our heads. Sooner or later, they're going to blow.
I'm not sure this is a good idea.
What do you mean?
Wrong. Your business is mine. We're entwined, thanks to this.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shadowheart taps a finger against/gestures to her temple (whichever can be accomplished)

Text.Value: Sure what is a good idea?
Either way, be careful. You never know what lengths someone might take to solve this little problem of ours.
You don't trust Gale?
That sort of danger - I'm fine with. I can fight it.
What were you two talking about?
Don't play the fool, please.

EditorData.logicalname: Fallback - Spoke to Undetermined Party First

Text.Value: I'd be careful with Astarion.
We need to get rid of them.
You and Wyll.
So am I.
Well, what do we really know about them...?
Maybe we will get lucky. We're overdue some good fortune.
This is unfamiliar territory. Rushing will only land us in more trouble than we can handle.
Get some rest. We move at dawn.
Fine. Just don't expect my confidence if I don't have yours.
You should get some rest. We've got hard times ahead.
Doing the rounds, are you? You'd better get some rest.
Relax. This camp seems safe from threats.
You don't trust Astarion?
I'd be careful with Gale.

EditorData.NodeContext: Gale pronounced same as the wind

Text.Value: Don't question me.
Heroic types can be brittle, I find. Better to trust someone with greater flexibility.
Let's not abandon all caution. This is unfamiliar territory.
I was merely making an observation.
You strike me as the reliable sort, but are you sure this is a good idea?

EditorData.NodeContext: Questioning, but in a respectful way.
EditorData.logicalname: Higher Approval Speak to Shadowheart first

Text.Value: Caution is a luxury we don't have. Let's rest and wake up at first light.
I'd be careful with Lae'zel.
Let's hope we rapidly find a healer.
Fine. But it won't be easy, searching this wilderness.
And just to be clear, come daybreak, finding a healer is our first priority.
If that was any of your business, we'd have called you over.
What were you two talking about?
They make the best servants.
Trust is a rare currency. Not sure I'd spend it on someone who drew a knife on me moments after I met them.
Oh, it's going to be like that? I love strong men.
Oh, it's going to be like that? I love strong women.
Oh, it's going to be like that? I love strong ones.
I'd be careful with who you confide in.

Text.Value: You seem reliable. I think you know how important it is that we find someone who can cure us. Best if we focus on that.

Text.Value: Spare me the petty tyrant routine - you're better than that.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: If SH's approval of  the player is greater than 0
EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly miffed. Thinks the player's dismissive response is beneath them

Synopsis: The party has stopped to camp for the first time. The player can speak to Shadowheart as they rest. She restates the urgent need to find a healer who can help them with their tadpole problem. If the player elected to confide in other party members ahead of her she'll caution that they may not be trustworthy.
